Compute $a \cdot b \cdot c \div d$ if\begin{align*}
a&=15 \\
b&=2002 \\
c&=3 \\
d&=1001.
\end{align*}

}

\large

\textbf{Answer:} Substituting the given values, we find $15 \cdot 2002 \cdot 3 \div 1001$. Notice that 2002 is twice 1001, so if we rewrite the division as multiplication, we can make the computation easier:\begin{align*}
15 \cdot 2002 \cdot 3 \div 1001&=15 \cdot 2002 \cdot 3 \cdot \frac{1}{1001} \\
&=15 \cdot 2002 \cdot \frac{1}{1001} \cdot 3 \\
&=15 \cdot \left(2002 \cdot \frac{1}{1001}\right) \cdot 3 \\
&=15 \cdot (2002 \div 1001) \cdot 3 \\
&=15 \cdot 2 \cdot 3 \\
&=30 \cdot 3 \\
&=\boxed{90}.
\end{align*}

}
